From cou.: 0 Journal
From Soup: 0 Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 The application of a genetic algorithm, for optimizing the geometries of stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric MgO clusters, bound by a simple Coulomb-plus-Born–Mayer potential, is investigated. The genetic algorithm is shown to be efficient and reliable for finding, reproducibly the global minima for these clusters. The variation of the structures of MgO clusters are investigated as a function of the formal charges (±q) on the ions—ranging from q=1 to q=2. In agreement with previous studies, lower charges are found to favour compact, rocksalt-like cuboidal clusters, while the higher formal charges favour hollow pseudo-spherical structures. Hexagonal stacks are also found to be stable for small (MgO)N clusters with N=3n. Comparisons are made with experimental mass spectral abundances and the results of previous empirical calculations, as well as with more sophisticated model potential and ab initio calculations. Finally, possible ways in which the genetic algorithm search method could be coupled with more accurate calculation methods are discussed.
From Soup: 1 The application of a genetic algorithm, for optimizing the geometries of stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric MgO clusters, bound by a simple Coulomb-plus-Born–Mayer potential, is investigated. The genetic algorithm is shown to be efficient and reliable for finding, reproducibly the global minima for these clusters. The variation of the structures of MgO clusters are investigated as a function of the formal charges (± q ) on the ions—ranging from q = 1 to q = 2. In agreement with previous studies, lower charges are found to favour compact, rocksalt-like cuboidal clusters, while the higher formal charges favour hollow pseudo-spherical structures. Hexagonal stacks are also found to be stable for small (MgO) N clusters with N = 3 n . Comparisons are made with experimental mass spectral abundances and the results of previous empirical calculations, as well as with more sophisticated model potential and ab initio calculations. Finally, possible ways in which the genetic algorithm search method could be coupled with more accurate calculation methods are discussed.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Ionic clusters are derived from ionic solids—compounds formed between electropositive metals and electronegative non-metals. The bonding in ionic clusters is primarily due to electrostatic interactions, and the simplicity of modelling ionic clusters makes them ideal systems in which to study size-dependent properties.1–3 Ionic clusters also have a growing number of practical applications, such as: silver halides in the photographic process; ZnS clusters as gas sensors; CdS and CdSe clusters as photodetectors; and polar semiconductors made from GaAs and InP clusters. The study of NaCl and NaBr clusters is also important in determining the mechanisms of ozone depletion and pollution in marine environments.
From Soup: 2 Ionic clusters are derived from ionic solids—compounds formed between electropositive metals and electronegative non-metals. The bonding in ionic clusters is primarily due to electrostatic interactions, and the simplicity of modelling ionic clusters makes them ideal systems in which to study size-dependent properties. 1–3 Ionic clusters also have a growing number of practical applications, such as: silver halides in the photographic process; ZnS clusters as gas sensors; CdS and CdSe clusters as photodetectors; and polar semiconductors made from GaAs and InP clusters. The study of NaCl and NaBr clusters is also important in determining the mechanisms of ozone depletion and pollution in marine environments.
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 There have been many experimental and theoretical studies of clusters of magnesium oxide (MgO), perhaps because it is the simplest ionic oxide species, crystallising in the rock salt (NaCl) structure. It is also hoped that a detailed understanding of the growth of (MgO)N clusters will lead to an improved understanding of epitaxial growth of MgO surfaces. MgO clusters have also been invoked as possible nucleation sites for the formation of particulate matter in oxygen-rich regions of space.
From Soup: 3 There have been many experimental and theoretical studies of clusters of magnesium oxide (MgO), perhaps because it is the simplest ionic oxide species, crystallising in the rock salt (NaCl) structure. It is also hoped that a detailed understanding of the growth of (MgO) N clusters will lead to an improved understanding of epitaxial growth of MgO surfaces. MgO clusters have also been invoked as possible nucleation sites for the formation of particulate matter in oxygen-rich regions of space.
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 In the late 1980s, Saunders published mass spectra and collision-induced fragmentation data for sputtered stoichiometric MgO cluster ions, (MgO)N+ (6≤N≤24), and found magic number peaks for N=6, 9, 12 and 15.4,5 These results were interpreted in terms of clusters built from hexagonal (MgO)3 sub-units. In the early 1990s, Ziemann and Castleman also studied (MgO)N+ clusters (N≤90), which were generated in a gas aggregation source and investigated using laser-ionization time of flight mass spectrometry.6,7 They found magic number clusters for (MgO)N+ at N=2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 24, 27 and 30—again showing a regular gap of 3 MgO “molecules”. For larger clusters, however, Ziemann and Castleman interpreted the mass spectral abundances in terms of MgO clusters having compact cuboidal (rock salt) structures, similar to those observed for alkali-halide clusters,2 and postulated that even the smaller clusters may have structures based on compact packing of Mg4O4 cubes.7
From Soup: 4 In the late 1980s, Saunders published mass spectra and collision-induced fragmentation data for sputtered stoichiometric MgO cluster ions, (MgO) N + (6 ≤ N ≤ 24), and found magic number peaks for N = 6, 9, 12 and 15. 4,5 These results were interpreted in terms of clusters built from hexagonal (MgO) 3 sub-units. In the early 1990s, Ziemann and Castleman also studied (MgO) N + clusters ( N ≤ 90), which were generated in a gas aggregation source and investigated using laser-ionization time of flight mass spectrometry . 6,7 They found magic number clusters for (MgO) N + at N = 2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 24, 27 and 30—again showing a regular gap of 3 MgO “molecules”. For larger clusters, however, Ziemann and Castleman interpreted the mass spectral abundances in terms of MgO clusters having compact cuboidal (rock salt) structures, similar to those observed for alkali- halide clusters, 2 and postulated that even the smaller clusters may have structures based on compact packing of Mg 4 O 4 cubes. 7
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 By varying the experimental conditions (e.g. by varying the flow rate of the carrier gas in a gas aggregation cluster source), Ziemann and Castleman also detected non-stoichiometric, Mg-rich (MgO)NMg+ (N≤90) and (MgO)NMg2+ (4≤N≤172) cluster ions.6–8 In the case of the (MgO)NMg+ and (MgO)NMg2+ clusters, magic numbers were observed for N=8, 11, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25 and 278 (as well as (MgO)35Mg+). These peaks were attributed to compact cuboidal (or defective cuboidal) structures.7,8
From Soup: 5 By varying the experimental conditions ( e.g. by varying the flow rate of the carrier gas in a gas aggregation cluster source), Ziemann and Castleman also detected non-stoichiometric, Mg-rich (MgO) N Mg + ( N ≤ 90) and (MgO) N Mg 2+ (4 ≤ N ≤ 172) cluster ions. 6–8 In the case of the (MgO) N Mg + and (MgO) N Mg 2+ clusters, magic numbers were observed for N = 8, 11, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25 and 27 8 (as well as (MgO) 35 Mg + ). These peaks were attributed to compact cuboidal (or defective cuboidal) structures. 7,8
