From cou.: 18 For a given cluster nuclearity (N), a number of clusters, Npop (typically ranging from 10 to 30) are generated at random to form the initial population (the “zeroth generation”). The real-valued cartesian x, y and z coordinates are chosen randomly in the range [0, N1/3] (and then scaled by the characteristic length, re, of the potential). This ensures that the cluster volume scales correctly with cluster size, i.e. linearly with N. Each cluster is then relaxed by locally minimizing the cluster potential energy as a function of the cluster coordinates.
From Soup: 18 For a given cluster nuclearity ( N ), a number of clusters, N pop (typically ranging from 10 to 30) are generated at random to form the initial population (the “zeroth generation”). The real-valued cartesian x , y and z coordinates are chosen randomly in the range [0, N 1/3 ] (and then scaled by the characteristic length, r e , of the potential). This ensures that the cluster volume scales correctly with cluster size, i.e . linearly with N . Each cluster is then relaxed by locally minimizing the cluster potential energy as a function of the cluster coordinates.
 ###### 
From cou.: 19 Each cluster is assigned a fitness value, based on its total potential energy (Vclus), such that low energy clusters (more negative Vclus) have high fitness and high energy clusters (less negative Vclus) have low fitness. In this work we have used a hyperbolic tangent (tanh) function, with the fitness (Fi) of the ith member of the population (with Vclus=Vi) given by:where dynamic fitness scaling is achieved by introducing the dimensionless quantity ρ:and Vmax and Vmin are the Vclus values of the highest and lowest energy clusters in the current population.
From Soup: 19 Each cluster is assigned a fitness value, based on its total potential energy ( V clus ), such that low energy clusters (more negative V clus ) have high fitness and high energy clusters (less negative V clus ) have low fitness. In this work we have used a hyperbolic tangent (tanh) function, with the fitness ( F i ) of the i th member of the population (with V clus = V i ) given by: where dynamic fitness scaling is achieved by introducing the dimensionless quantity ρ : and V max and V min are the V clus values of the highest and lowest energy clusters in the current population.
