From cou.: 20 The selection of parents for mating is accomplished using a variant of the roulette wheel method.26 A cluster is picked at random and is accepted for mating if its fitness value (Fi) is greater than a randomly generated number between 0 and 1 (i.e. if Fi>R[0,1]). If the candidate cluster is rejected for mating, then another is picked and the process is repeated. In this way, low energy clusters (with high fitness values) are more likely to be selected for mating and, therefore, to pass on their structural characteristics. Although a particular cluster may be chosen more than once for mating, within each pair of parents, the same cluster cannot be chosen twice. Once a pair of parents have been selected for mating, they are subjected to the crossover operation.
From Soup: 20 The selection of parents for mating is accomplished using a variant of the roulette wheel method. 26 A cluster is picked at random and is accepted for mating if its fitness value ( F i ) is greater than a randomly generated number between 0 and 1 ( i.e . if F i > R [0,1]). If the candidate cluster is rejected for mating, then another is picked and the process is repeated. In this way, low energy clusters (with high fitness values) are more likely to be selected for mating and, therefore, to pass on their structural characteristics. Although a particular cluster may be chosen more than once for mating, within each pair of parents, the same cluster cannot be chosen twice. Once a pair of parents have been selected for mating, they are subjected to the crossover operation.
 ###### 
From cou.: 21 Crossover is carried out using a modified version of the cut and splice crossover operator of Deaven and Ho.37 In our implementation of the cut and splice operation, as shown schematically in Fig. 2, random rotations (about two perpendicular axes) are performed on both parent clusters and then both clusters are cut horizontally—parallel to the xy plane and complementary fragments are spliced together. For single-element clusters, this is accomplished by ranking the coordinates of the component atoms of each rotated cluster in order of decreasing z coordinate and then selecting the first (highest z) N−M coordinates from the first parent and the last (lowest z) M coordinates from the second parent and combining them to generate a single offspring cluster with N atoms.
From Soup: 21 Crossover is carried out using a modified version of the cut and splice crossover operator of Deaven and Ho. 37 In our implementation of the cut and splice operation, as shown schematically in Fig. 2 , random rotations (about two perpendicular axes) are performed on both parent clusters and then both clusters are cut horizontally—parallel to the xy plane and complementary fragments are spliced together. For single-element clusters, this is accomplished by ranking the coordinates of the component atoms of each rotated cluster in order of decreasing z coordinate and then selecting the first (highest z ) N − M coordinates from the first parent and the last (lowest z ) M coordinates from the second parent and combining them to generate a single offspring cluster with N atoms.
 ###### 
From cou.: 22 For heteroatomic clusters, such as ionic clusters, the crossover procedure has been modified in order to preserve the correct number of atoms of each type in the cluster. It is not possible to simply cut and splice the clusters about an arbitrary position as there is no guarantee that the correct stoichiometry would be retained. A weighted splice position, Npos, is instead generated (calculated from the relative fitness values). The first 1 to Npos atoms are copied from the first cluster, irrespective of the atom type. The number of atoms of each type, Ntype1 and Ntype2, copied during this process are counted. The remainder of the cluster is then formed from the Ntype1+1 to Natoms1 atoms of type one and the Ntype2+1 to Natoms2 atoms of type 2 from the second parent.
From Soup: 22 For heteroatomic clusters, such as ionic clusters, the crossover procedure has been modified in order to preserve the correct number of atoms of each type in the cluster. It is not possible to simply cut and splice the clusters about an arbitrary position as there is no guarantee that the correct stoichiometry would be retained. A weighted splice position, N pos , is instead generated (calculated from the relative fitness values). The first 1 to N pos atoms are copied from the first cluster, irrespective of the atom type. The number of atoms of each type, N type1 and N type2 , copied during this process are counted. The remainder of the cluster is then formed from the N type1 + 1 to N atoms1 atoms of type one and the N type2 + 1 to N atoms2 atoms of type 2 from the second parent.
 ###### 
From cou.: 23 Mating continues until a predetermined number of offspring (Nmat) have been generated. The number of matings is generally set to approximately 80% of the population size. Unless selected for mutation, each offspring cluster is subsequently locally minimized.
From Soup: 23 Mating continues until a predetermined number of offspring ( N mat ) have been generated. The number of matings is generally set to approximately 80% of the population size. Unless selected for mutation, each offspring cluster is subsequently locally minimized.
 ###### 
From cou.: 24 While the mating/crossover operation leads to a mixing of genetic material in the offspring, no new genetic material is introduced. In an attempt to avoid population stagnation (i.e. to maintain population diversity), a mutation operator is introduced. Within our GA, mutation is performed on the set of Nmat offspring, with each offspring cluster having the same probability (Pmut) of being mutated.
From Soup: 24 While the mating/crossover operation leads to a mixing of genetic material in the offspring, no new genetic material is introduced. In an attempt to avoid population stagnation ( i.e . to maintain population diversity), a mutation operator is introduced. Within our GA, mutation is performed on the set of N mat offspring, with each offspring cluster having the same probability ( P mut ) of being mutated.
