 ###### 
From cou.: 26 Rotate mutation involves rotation of the upper half of the cluster relative to the bottom half, by a random angle about the z axis.
From Soup: 26 After mutation, clusters are again locally minimized. The form of the rigid ion potential is such that the potential becomes highly attractive at very short range. If a mating or mutation operation places two atoms of opposite charge very close together, then on minimization of the energy, the cluster collapses due to the attractive −1/ r term overcoming the repulsive Born–Mayer term (which has an exponential form). In the modified program, therefore, if the energy of the cluster is very low after energy minimization, signifying that the cluster has collapsed, then a new cluster is generated at random to replace it. The energy of the new cluster is then relaxed to the nearest local minimum. A brief study of “atom-replacement” mutation (involving randomly moving a small number of atoms 34 ) showed that this mutation scheme was inefficient, as there was too great a tendency to generate structures which collapse upon minimization.
 ###### 
From cou.: 27 Exchange mutation permutes the atom types of a pair of atoms without perturbing the structure of the cluster. Approximately N/3 atom label swaps are performed per cluster mutation.
From Soup: 27 The next stage of the GA involves selecting the N pop lowest energy clusters to form the next generation. The set of N pop “old” clusters (from the previous generation) and N mat “new” clusters (offspring and mutants) are ranked in order of potential energy. The top N pop clusters ( i.e . those with lowest energy) are then selected to constitute the next generation. This selection process is the analogue of natural selection in biological evolution.
 ###### 
From cou.: 28 After mutation, clusters are again locally minimized. The form of the rigid ion potential is such that the potential becomes highly attractive at very short range. If a mating or mutation operation places two atoms of opposite charge very close together, then on minimization of the energy, the cluster collapses due to the attractive −1/r term overcoming the repulsive Born–Mayer term (which has an exponential form). In the modified program, therefore, if the energy of the cluster is very low after energy minimization, signifying that the cluster has collapsed, then a new cluster is generated at random to replace it. The energy of the new cluster is then relaxed to the nearest local minimum. A brief study of “atom-replacement” mutation (involving randomly moving a small number of atoms34) showed that this mutation scheme was inefficient, as there was too great a tendency to generate structures which collapse upon minimization.
From Soup: 28 The whole process of mating, mutation and selection is repeated for a specified number ( N gen ) of generations.
