From cou.: 30 The whole process of mating, mutation and selection is repeated for a specified number (Ngen) of generations.
From Soup: 30 Fig. 3 shows the percentage efficiency of the GA, measured over 20 different runs of the GA, for clusters of 20 to 70 ions ( i.e . (MgO) 10 –(MgO) 35 ), for formal charges of Mg + and O − (see following discussion). The success of the GA was assessed according to how often the lowest energy (assumed global minimum) structure was found. For these calculations, the GA parameters were: roulette wheel selection, with the tanh fitness function and fitness-weighted crossover; N pop = 20; N mat = 16; and both exchange and rotate mutations were compared (with P mut = 0.05). The GA was run for a maximum of N gen = 200 generations.
 ###### 
From cou.: 31 Graphical representations and atomic coordinates of the clusters found as global minima by our GA search program (some of which are discussed below) can be found on the Birmingham Cluster Web page.38
From Soup: 31 As can be seen in Fig. 3 , the efficiency of the GA lies in the range 70–100% for all of the cluster nuclearities considered, with two exceptions—for 50 ((MgO) 25 ) and 54 ((MgO) 27 ) ions. The GA results are also generally very reproducible. The global minimum of the 50-ion cluster has a 5 × 5 × 2 cuboidal structure, while the slightly higher energy (metastable) isomers of (MgO) 25 have structures based on the more cubic 4 × 4 × 3 48-ion cluster. It is difficult for the GA operators to construct the 5 × 5 × 2 structure from those based on the 4 × 4 × 3 structure, which is reflected in the relatively low efficiency (5%, i.e . only once in 20 runs) of the GA in locating the 5 × 5 × 2 structure. Of course, this reduces the confidence with which we can say that we have found the GM for (MgO) 25 . The low efficiency of the GA in locating the 54-ion global minimum cluster (25% or 45%, depending on the mutation operator) has a similar origin, as this structure has a 6 × 3 × 3 cuboidal configuration, which again is significantly different from the structures of clusters based on the 4 × 4 × 3 structure. Doye and Wales have carried out a detailed study of the dynamics of the (NaCl) 35 Cl − cluster, showing that interconversion between different family of rock salt cuboids can be a slow process. 39–41 Different isomers of charged NaCl clusters have also been detected and distinguished by Dugourd, Jarrold and co-workers, on the basis of their differing mobilities in drift tube experiments. 42 These workers have also studied the dynamical interconversion of NaCl cluster isomers. 43
 ###### 
From cou.: 32 Fig. 3 shows the percentage efficiency of the GA, measured over 20 different runs of the GA, for clusters of 20 to 70 ions (i.e. (MgO)10–(MgO)35), for formal charges of Mg+ and O− (see following discussion). The success of the GA was assessed according to how often the lowest energy (assumed global minimum) structure was found. For these calculations, the GA parameters were: roulette wheel selection, with the tanh fitness function and fitness-weighted crossover; Npop=20; Nmat=16; and both exchange and rotate mutations were compared (with Pmut=0.05). The GA was run for a maximum of Ngen=200 generations.
From Soup: 32 Fig. 3 also shows that changing the mutation operator has little effect on the efficiency of the GA, in fact the graphs overlap for most nuclearities. This is probably because structures with adjacent ions of the same charge are strongly discriminated against on energy (and hence fitness) grounds, so that the exchange mutation operation is very unlikely to lead to low energy mutants. We have found, however, that this mutation operation is useful in determining the global minima of mixed-metal alloy clusters, where there is no repulsive interaction between species of the same type. 34,44
 ###### 
From cou.: 33 As can be seen in Fig. 3, the efficiency of the GA lies in the range 70–100% for all of the cluster nuclearities considered, with two exceptions—for 50 ((MgO)25) and 54 ((MgO)27) ions. The GA results are also generally very reproducible. The global minimum of the 50-ion cluster has a 5×5×2 cuboidal structure, while the slightly higher energy (metastable) isomers of (MgO)25 have structures based on the more cubic 4×4×3 48-ion cluster. It is difficult for the GA operators to construct the 5×5×2 structure from those based on the 4×4×3 structure, which is reflected in the relatively low efficiency (5%, i.e. only once in 20 runs) of the GA in locating the 5×5×2 structure. Of course, this reduces the confidence with which we can say that we have found the GM for (MgO)25. The low efficiency of the GA in locating the 54-ion global minimum cluster (25% or 45%, depending on the mutation operator) has a similar origin, as this structure has a 6×3×3 cuboidal configuration, which again is significantly different from the structures of clusters based on the 4×4×3 structure. Doye and Wales have carried out a detailed study of the dynamics of the (NaCl)35Cl− cluster, showing that interconversion between different family of rock salt cuboids can be a slow process.39–41 Different isomers of charged NaCl clusters have also been detected and distinguished by Dugourd, Jarrold and co-workers, on the basis of their differing mobilities in drift tube experiments.42 These workers have also studied the dynamical interconversion of NaCl cluster isomers.43
From Soup: 33 The ions in MgO have formal charges of Mg 2+ and O 2− , but, following the approach of Ziemann and Castleman, 7 we have used the cluster GA to optimize the geometries of stoichiometric (MgO) N clusters ( N = 10–35), with formal ionic charges of Mg + O − , as well as Mg 2+ O 2− . The same GA parameters were used as in the first study, though only the rotate mutation operation was adopted.
 ###### 
From cou.: 34 Fig. 3 also shows that changing the mutation operator has little effect on the efficiency of the GA, in fact the graphs overlap for most nuclearities. This is probably because structures with adjacent ions of the same charge are strongly discriminated against on energy (and hence fitness) grounds, so that the exchange mutation operation is very unlikely to lead to low energy mutants. We have found, however, that this mutation operation is useful in determining the global minima of mixed-metal alloy clusters, where there is no repulsive interaction between species of the same type.34,44
From Soup: 34 The binding energies per ion ( E b ) of these clusters are listed in Table 2 and the structures of the Mg + O − and Mg 2+ O 2− clusters are shown in Fig. 4 and 5 , respectively, for 10 to 35 ion pairs. The lowest energy Mg + O − clusters can be seen to be compact cuboidal structures based on the NaCl structure (the structure of bulk MgO), whereas the Mg 2+ O 2− clusters are more spherical, hollow, cage-like structures with square, hexagonal and octagonal faces. The shorter equilibrium bond length of a pair of doubly charged ions forces all ions closer together in the cluster, which increases the repulsion between like ions. The repulsion is much greater between ions of like charges in the Mg q + O q − clusters with q = 2, compared with those with q = 1. This causes the cluster structures to open out from highly coordinated cuboids for q = 1 to hollow cages for q = 2. 7
 ###### 
From cou.: 35 The ions in MgO have formal charges of Mg2+ and O2−, but, following the approach of Ziemann and Castleman,7 we have used the cluster GA to optimize the geometries of stoichiometric (MgO)N clusters (N=10–35), with formal ionic charges of Mg+O−, as well as Mg2+O2−. The same GA parameters were used as in the first study, though only the rotate mutation operation was adopted.
From Soup: 35 The rigid ion potential does not contain any terms to describe the polarization of ions in a system, and, as the O 2− ions are highly polarizable and the Mg 2+ ions are strongly polarizing, the rigid ion model provides a poor description of Mg 2+ O 2− clusters. The effect of polarization will be to reduce the effective charges of both ions, thereby reducing the repulsion felt between like ions. This will lead to the more highly coordinated (bulk-like) cuboidal structures being preferred over the cage like structures, due to the higher degree of bonding present. The rigid ion model calculations used singly charged ions in order to mimic, partially the effect of polarizability. Calculations using potentials that include explicit terms for the polarizability of the cluster ions 17 and ab initio 13–16 calculations predict cubic structures to be the group state configurations of MgO clusters, at least for clusters of upwards of 20–30 ion pairs. It should be noted, however, that the ab initio calculations have, by necessity, involved searching rather small regions of configuration space, close to bulk-like geometries or those produced from more exhaustive rigid ion model searches.
 ###### 
From cou.: 36 The binding energies per ion (Eb) of these clusters are listed in Table 2 and the structures of the Mg+O− and Mg2+O2− clusters are shown in Fig. 4 and 5, respectively, for 10 to 35 ion pairs. The lowest energy Mg+O− clusters can be seen to be compact cuboidal structures based on the NaCl structure (the structure of bulk MgO), whereas the Mg2+O2− clusters are more spherical, hollow, cage-like structures with square, hexagonal and octagonal faces. The shorter equilibrium bond length of a pair of doubly charged ions forces all ions closer together in the cluster, which increases the repulsion between like ions. The repulsion is much greater between ions of like charges in the Mgq+Oq− clusters with q=2, compared with those with q=1. This causes the cluster structures to open out from highly coordinated cuboids for q=1 to hollow cages for q=2.7
From Soup: 36 As mentioned in the introduction, the experimental mass spectra of Ziemann and Castleman 6–8 showed magic number clusters (corresponding to relatively intense peaks): for (MgO) N + at N = 2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 24, 27, and 30; for (MgO) N Mg + at N = 8, 11, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25, and 27; and for (MgO) N Mg 2+ at N = 8, 11, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25, and 27. These results have been interpreted in terms of clusters with compact cuboidal (rock salt) structures, as predicted by the rigid ion model for ionic charges of +1 and −1, 7 though Wilson and others have postulated that some of the magic numbers ( i.e. those with N = 3 n ) may be due to hexagonal stacks or “ nanotubes ”. 15,17
 ###### 
From cou.: 37 The rigid ion potential does not contain any terms to describe the polarization of ions in a system, and, as the O2− ions are highly polarizable and the Mg2+ ions are strongly polarizing, the rigid ion model provides a poor description of Mg2+O2− clusters. The effect of polarization will be to reduce the effective charges of both ions, thereby reducing the repulsion felt between like ions. This will lead to the more highly coordinated (bulk-like) cuboidal structures being preferred over the cage like structures, due to the higher degree of bonding present. The rigid ion model calculations used singly charged ions in order to mimic, partially the effect of polarizability. Calculations using potentials that include explicit terms for the polarizability of the cluster ions17 and ab initio13–16 calculations predict cubic structures to be the group state configurations of MgO clusters, at least for clusters of upwards of 20–30 ion pairs. It should be noted, however, that the ab initio calculations have, by necessity, involved searching rather small regions of configuration space, close to bulk-like geometries or those produced from more exhaustive rigid ion model searches.
From Soup: 37 Ziemann and Castleman have also performed calculations based on the rigid ion model, 7 using two different Born–Mayer repulsive potentials and formal charges of q = 1 and 2. They found similar trends in the structures to those produced by our GA optimization: namely cuboidal structures for q = 1 and cage structures for q = 2. For singly charged ions with fewer than 20 or 50 ions, however (depending on which Born–Mayer potential was used), structures based on stacked hexagons or octagons were found to be competitive with the cuboidal geometries, which is consistent with the calculations of Wilson. 17 In fact, Wilson has stated that the occurrence of low-lying hexagonal stack structures makes the MgO clusters more similar to those of LiF or NaI, rather than NaCl or KCl. 17 The occurrence of hexagonal structures for LiF and NaI clusters has been attributed to polarization effects. 17 In the case of NaI, this is due to the relatively high polarizability of the large iodide anion. For LiF clusters, however, although the fluoride anion is significantly less polarizable than the heavier halide anions , the polarizing effect of the small Li + cation is much larger than that of Na + or K + .
 ###### 
From cou.: 38 As mentioned in the introduction, the experimental mass spectra of Ziemann and Castleman6–8 showed magic number clusters (corresponding to relatively intense peaks): for (MgO)N+ at N=2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 15, 18, 24, 27, and 30; for (MgO)NMg+ at N=8, 11, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25, and 27; and for (MgO)NMg2+ at N=8, 11, 13, 16, 19, 22, 25, and 27. These results have been interpreted in terms of clusters with compact cuboidal (rock salt) structures, as predicted by the rigid ion model for ionic charges of +1 and −1,7 though Wilson and others have postulated that some of the magic numbers (i.e. those with N=3n) may be due to hexagonal stacks or “nanotubes”.15,17
From Soup: 38 As shown in Fig. 4 , for (MgO) N clusters (with N in the range 10–35) the cluster GA found clusters with complete cuboidal lattice structures for Mg + O − ) N clusters with N = 12 (4 × 3 × 2), 15 (5 × 3 × 2), 16 (4 × 4 × 2), 18 (4 × 3 × 3), 20 (5 × 4 × 2), 24 (4 × 4 × 3), 25 (5 × 5 × 2), 27 (6 × 3 × 3), 30 (5 × 4 × 3) and 32 (4 × 4 × 4)). Most of these match the magic numbers observed experimentally by Ziemann and Castleman. 7
 ###### 
From cou.: 39 Ziemann and Castleman have also performed calculations based on the rigid ion model,7 using two different Born–Mayer repulsive potentials and formal charges of q=1 and 2. They found similar trends in the structures to those produced by our GA optimization: namely cuboidal structures for q=1 and cage structures for q=2. For singly charged ions with fewer than 20 or 50 ions, however (depending on which Born–Mayer potential was used), structures based on stacked hexagons or octagons were found to be competitive with the cuboidal geometries, which is consistent with the calculations of Wilson.17 In fact, Wilson has stated that the occurrence of low-lying hexagonal stack structures makes the MgO clusters more similar to those of LiF or NaI, rather than NaCl or KCl.17 The occurrence of hexagonal structures for LiF and NaI clusters has been attributed to polarization effects.17 In the case of NaI, this is due to the relatively high polarizability of the large iodide anion. For LiF clusters, however, although the fluoride anion is significantly less polarizable than the heavier halide anions, the polarizing effect of the small Li+ cation is much larger than that of Na+ or K+.
From Soup: 39 The structures found by the GA for the global minima of (Mg 2+ O 2− ) N clusters (see Fig. 5 ) are very similar to those found by Ziemann and Castleman, 7 though there are some differences, notably for (MgO) 13 , where their structure has a basket-plus-handle geometry, with two ions having only two neighbours, while ours is more compact. This may be due to their having used a different Born–Mayer repulsive potential, although it is possible that their search algorithm (which is essentially a random search procedure) did not find the true global minimum for some of these clusters. On the basis of previous work, however, it should be said that the structures produced for the rigid ion model, with formal charges of ±2 are incompatible with the observed mass spectra and are, therefore, unlikely to represent the true structures of MgO clusters.
 ###### 
From cou.: 40 As shown in Fig. 4, for (MgO)N clusters (with N in the range 10–35) the cluster GA found clusters with complete cuboidal lattice structures for Mg+O−)N clusters with N=12 (4×3×2), 15 (5×3×2), 16 (4×4×2), 18 (4×3×3), 20 (5×4×2), 24 (4×4×3), 25 (5×5×2), 27 (6×3×3), 30 (5×4×3) and 32 (4×4×4)). Most of these match the magic numbers observed experimentally by Ziemann and Castleman.7
