From Soup: 43 The largest peaks in the second difference plot for Mg + O − clusters correspond to structures having complete i × j × k cuboidal lattice structures (see Fig. 4 ), as such structures maximise the number of attractive cation –anion contacts. The peaks in E 2nd correspond to the peaks in dissociation energy (for loss of MgO units) calculated by Ziemann and Castleman for (Mg + O − ) N clusters, within the rigid ion model, 7 both being in good agreement with the most intense peaks in the mass spectrum of MgO clusters.
 ###### 
From cou.: 44 The largest peaks in the second difference plot for Mg+O− clusters correspond to structures having complete i×j×k cuboidal lattice structures (see Fig. 4), as such structures maximise the number of attractive cation–anion contacts. The peaks in E2nd correspond to the peaks in dissociation energy (for loss of MgO units) calculated by Ziemann and Castleman for (Mg+O−)N clusters, within the rigid ion model,7 both being in good agreement with the most intense peaks in the mass spectrum of MgO clusters.
From Soup: 44 It should be noted that the lowest energy structure for (Mg + O − ) 21 ( N ions = 42) is not a 7 × 3 × 2 cuboid, but rather it has a step structure. This may be because the very aspherical cuboidal structure has too high a surface area and hence a lower binding energy. This may also explain the relatively low binding energy of (Mg + O − ) 25 ( N ions = 50), since the 5 × 5 × 2 cuboid is very flat and again has a high surface energy, though apparently, for this geometry there is no alternative geometry of lower energy.
 ###### 
From cou.: 45 It should be noted that the lowest energy structure for (Mg+O−)21 (Nions=42) is not a 7×3×2 cuboid, but rather it has a step structure. This may be because the very aspherical cuboidal structure has too high a surface area and hence a lower binding energy. This may also explain the relatively low binding energy of (Mg+O−)25 (Nions=50), since the 5×5×2 cuboid is very flat and again has a high surface energy, though apparently, for this geometry there is no alternative geometry of lower energy.
From Soup: 45 3.2.1 Enantiomeric clusters.
 ###### 
From cou.: 46 3.2.1 Enantiomeric clusters.
From Soup: 46 For many of the cluster geometries found by the GA, enantiomers (non-super-imposable mirror-image structures) exist, due to the loss of mirror planes of symmetry in clusters composed of two distinct species. The enantiomers of the GM (Mg 2+ O 2− ) 30 structure are shown in Fig. 7 . Of course, these enantiomers have identical binding energies.
 ###### 
From cou.: 47 For many of the cluster geometries found by the GA, enantiomers (non-super-imposable mirror-image structures) exist, due to the loss of mirror planes of symmetry in clusters composed of two distinct species. The enantiomers of the GM (Mg2+O2−)30 structure are shown in Fig. 7. Of course, these enantiomers have identical binding energies.
From Soup: 47 Evolutionary progress plots (EPPs), 45 showing the convergence of the GA on the lowest energy (MgO) 30 clusters, with formal charges of ±1 and ±2 are shown in Fig. 8 . The figure shows that the GA required 74 generations to find the lowest energy structure of (Mg 2+ O 2− ) 30 but only 7 generations to find the lowest energy structure of (Mg + O − ) 30 . In both cases the minimum, maximum and average energies converge, indicating that the GA has converged on a single solution. The GA converges in 27 generations for q = 1 and in 100 generations for q = 2. These results are typical of the other cluster nuclearities studied. The rigid-ion potential with formal charges of ±2 is shorter ranged and the potential energy surface is therefore likely to have more local minima for the GA to search, leading to greater difficulty in finding the global minimum.
 ###### 
From cou.: 48 Evolutionary progress plots (EPPs),45 showing the convergence of the GA on the lowest energy (MgO)30 clusters, with formal charges of ±1 and ±2 are shown in Fig. 8. The figure shows that the GA required 74 generations to find the lowest energy structure of (Mg2+O2−)30 but only 7 generations to find the lowest energy structure of (Mg+O−)30. In both cases the minimum, maximum and average energies converge, indicating that the GA has converged on a single solution. The GA converges in 27 generations for q=1 and in 100 generations for q=2. These results are typical of the other cluster nuclearities studied. The rigid-ion potential with formal charges of ±2 is shorter ranged and the potential energy surface is therefore likely to have more local minima for the GA to search, leading to greater difficulty in finding the global minimum.
From Soup: 48 It should be noted that population convergence does not always signify that the GA has found the true GM, as premature convergence (stagnation), on a sub-optimal solution (a local minimum), is also possible. Population convergence corresponds to a loss of population diversity. Although premature convergence cannot be seen in Fig. 8 (assuming that we have found the true GM in both cases), previous studies have shown that premature convergence is not necessarily disastrous for our GA, 33,34 since diversity can be reintroduced into a population either by mutation or by crossover. The nature of the Deaven and Ho crossover operation, for example, means that, even for two identical parents, a variety of distinct offspring can be generated.
 ###### 
From cou.: 49 It should be noted that population convergence does not always signify that the GA has found the true GM, as premature convergence (stagnation), on a sub-optimal solution (a local minimum), is also possible. Population convergence corresponds to a loss of population diversity. Although premature convergence cannot be seen in Fig. 8 (assuming that we have found the true GM in both cases), previous studies have shown that premature convergence is not necessarily disastrous for our GA,33,34 since diversity can be reintroduced into a population either by mutation or by crossover. The nature of the Deaven and Ho crossover operation, for example, means that, even for two identical parents, a variety of distinct offspring can be generated.
From Soup: 49 As noted above, MgO clusters with formal ionic charges of ±1 and ±2 have different structures. To investigate the dependence of structure on charge further, we have studied the effect, on the lowest energy structures of small (Mg q + O q − ) N clusters, of varying the magnitude of the charge ( q ) in incre-ments of 0.1 from 1.0 to 2.0. In the following discussion, our results are compared with work by de la Puente et al. , 15 who studied neutral MgO clusters of between 6 and 13 ion pairs using HF (Hartree–Fock) and CHF (Coulomb–Hartree–Fock 46 ) ab initio techniques. The CHF method is a “perturbed ion” approach which includes intra-ion electron correlation corrections. Reference will also be made to the work of Recio et al. , 13 who performed HF and HF + MP2 (inclusion of second-order Møller–Plesset perturbation theory to account for electron correlation) calculations on MgO clusters. It should be noted, however, that these ab initio calculations were restricted to a number of assumed geometries, as an exhaustive search of the potential energy surface is ruled out due to excessive computational requirements. Finally, some comparison will be made with the rigid ion model calculations of Ziemann and Castleman. 7
 ###### 
From cou.: 50 As noted above, MgO clusters with formal ionic charges of ±1 and ±2 have different structures. To investigate the dependence of structure on charge further, we have studied the effect, on the lowest energy structures of small (Mgq+Oq−)N clusters, of varying the magnitude of the charge (q) in incre-ments of 0.1 from 1.0 to 2.0. In the following discussion, our results are compared with work by de la Puente et al.,15 who studied neutral MgO clusters of between 6 and 13 ion pairs using HF (Hartree–Fock) and CHF (Coulomb–Hartree–Fock46) ab initio techniques. The CHF method is a “perturbed ion” approach which includes intra-ion electron correlation corrections. Reference will also be made to the work of Recio et al.,13 who performed HF and HF+MP2 (inclusion of second-order Møller–Plesset perturbation theory to account for electron correlation) calculations on MgO clusters. It should be noted, however, that these ab initio calculations were restricted to a number of assumed geometries, as an exhaustive search of the potential energy surface is ruled out due to excessive computational requirements. Finally, some comparison will be made with the rigid ion model calculations of Ziemann and Castleman.7
From Soup: 50 The structure of the N = 6 cluster consists of two stacked hexagonal Mg 3 O 3 rings and does not vary with the charge of the ions. This is the ground state configuration predicted by de la Puente, Recio and Malliavin. 13,15,16
 ###### 
From cou.: 51 The structure of the N=6 cluster consists of two stacked hexagonal Mg3O3 rings and does not vary with the charge of the ions. This is the ground state configuration predicted by de la Puente, Recio and Malliavin.13,15,16
From Soup: 51 The geometry of the most stable N = 7 MgO cluster, changes from a cage type structure to that of two stacked hexagonal rings, one with an MgO pair protruding from an edge, when the charges are 1.8 or more, as shown in Fig. 9 . Both of these structures are found to be low energy configurations for both sets of calculations by de la Puente, with the HF calculations predicting the cage structure to be the global minimum. The HF calculations of Recio also find the cage-like structure to be lowest in energy, with an alternative structure, based on a hexagonal prism with a vertical, rather than horizontal edge bridged by an MgO unit, lying at slightly higher energy. The rigid ion model calculations of Ziemann and Castleman predict a monocyclic ring geometry for (Mg 2+ O 2− ) 7 , 7 as opposed to the stacked ring structures found for the N = 6 and N = 8 clusters. This is presumably a consequence of the inefficient search method adopted.
 ###### 
From cou.: 52 The geometry of the most stable N=7 MgO cluster, changes from a cage type structure to that of two stacked hexagonal rings, one with an MgO pair protruding from an edge, when the charges are 1.8 or more, as shown in Fig. 9. Both of these structures are found to be low energy configurations for both sets of calculations by de la Puente, with the HF calculations predicting the cage structure to be the global minimum. The HF calculations of Recio also find the cage-like structure to be lowest in energy, with an alternative structure, based on a hexagonal prism with a vertical, rather than horizontal edge bridged by an MgO unit, lying at slightly higher energy. The rigid ion model calculations of Ziemann and Castleman predict a monocyclic ring geometry for (Mg2+O2−)7,7 as opposed to the stacked ring structures found for the N=6 and N=8 clusters. This is presumably a consequence of the inefficient search method adopted.
From Soup: 52 As shown in Fig. 10 , for the rigid ion model, the (MgO) 8 cluster has three possible structures, a 4 × 2 × 2 lattice for q = 1.0–1.3, a cage structure for q = 1.4–1.6 and a structure consisting of two stacked octagonal rings for q = 1.7–2.0. Two more open structures can both be generated by lengthening different Mg–O contacts in the 4 × 2 × 2 cuboid. The stacked octagonal ring structure is the ground state structure predicted by the HF calculations of de la Puente and Recio, while the CHF calculations predict a structure of two hexagonal MgO rings with an Mg 2 O 2 square capping one of the square faces. 15
 ###### 
From cou.: 53 As shown in Fig. 10, for the rigid ion model, the (MgO)8 cluster has three possible structures, a 4×2×2 lattice for q=1.0–1.3, a cage structure for q=1.4–1.6 and a structure consisting of two stacked octagonal rings for q=1.7–2.0. Two more open structures can both be generated by lengthening different Mg–O contacts in the 4×2×2 cuboid. The stacked octagonal ring structure is the ground state structure predicted by the HF calculations of de la Puente and Recio, while the CHF calculations predict a structure of two hexagonal MgO rings with an Mg2O2 square capping one of the square faces.15
From Soup: 53 In contrast to the N = 8 cluster, the same geometry was found for (MgO) 9 for q = 1.0–2.0: corresponding to three stacked hexagonal Mg 3 O 3 rings, as shown in Fig. 11 . This geometry is the ground state structure found, using both the HF and CHF methods, by de la Puente and by Recio et al. as well as Ziemann and Castleman for q = 2.
