From cou.: 57 The three different structures found by the GA for N=12 MgO clusters are shown in Fig. 14. The structure found when the charges are equal to 1.0 is a 4×3×2 lattice, the structure found when the charges are between 1.1 and 1.5 consists of 4 stacked MgO hexagons and the structure found when the charge is 1.6 or higher is the pseudo-spherical truncated octahedron, formed from MgO squares and hexagons. These three different structures are the three lowest energy isomers published by de la Puente for (MgO)12 clusters, with the truncated octahedron being the ground state configuration, for both HF and CHF calculations. The HF calculations of Recio predicted the hexagonal stack to lie lower in energy than the 4×3×2 cuboid — though they did not investigate the more spherical truncated octahedron, which was also found to be most stable by Ziemann and Castleman, within the rigid ion model, for q=2.
From Soup: 57 As shown in Fig. 15 , the geometry of the (MgO) 13 cluster, for q = 1.0–1.5 is that of a 3 × 3 × 2 lattice with an octagonal Mg 4 O 4 ring stacked above one of the 3 × 3 faces. This structure has an oxide ion at the centre. An alternative way of viewing this structure is as an O-centred 3 × 3 × 3 cube, with a Mg ion missing from the centre of one of the 3 × 3 cube faces, which then distorts to form an octagon. The ground state structure calculated by de la Puente, at both the HF and CHF levels, has the same oxide -ion centred geometry, with an analogous Mg-centred structure at higher energy. The lowest energy structure calculated by Recio et al. is an O-centred 3 × 3 × 3 cube, with a corner, rather than a face, (Mg) ion missing. The HF and CHF calculations of de la Puente et al. indicate, however, that this structure is higher in energy than the face-defect structure, which implies that Redo et al. did not search enough of the configuration space. When the charge is raised to 1.6 (or above) the resulting structure is a cage with square, hexagonal and octagonal faces. The lowest energy structure predicted by Ziemann and Castleman for (Mg 2+ O 2− ) 13 has a basket-shaped geometry, corresponding to a truncated octahedron, with one of the cluster edges replaced by an Mg–O unit.
 ###### 
From cou.: 58 As shown in Fig. 15, the geometry of the (MgO)13 cluster, for q=1.0–1.5 is that of a 3×3×2 lattice with an octagonal Mg4O4 ring stacked above one of the 3×3 faces. This structure has an oxide ion at the centre. An alternative way of viewing this structure is as an O-centred 3×3×3 cube, with a Mg ion missing from the centre of one of the 3×3 cube faces, which then distorts to form an octagon. The ground state structure calculated by de la Puente, at both the HF and CHF levels, has the same oxide-ion centred geometry, with an analogous Mg-centred structure at higher energy. The lowest energy structure calculated by Recio et al. is an O-centred 3×3×3 cube, with a corner, rather than a face, (Mg) ion missing. The HF and CHF calculations of de la Puente et al. indicate, however, that this structure is higher in energy than the face-defect structure, which implies that Redo et al. did not search enough of the configuration space. When the charge is raised to 1.6 (or above) the resulting structure is a cage with square, hexagonal and octagonal faces. The lowest energy structure predicted by Ziemann and Castleman for (Mg2+O2−)13 has a basket-shaped geometry, corresponding to a truncated octahedron, with one of the cluster edges replaced by an Mg–O unit.
From Soup: 58 It is interesting to note that these calculations have shown structures with oxide ions in the centre to be lower in energy than those with Mg ions in the centre. De la Puente et al. have attributed this to the enhanced electrostatic interaction stabilising highly charged anions in more highly coordinated sites, 15 although later arguments, based on anion polarizability, appear to contradict this. 19,20
 ###### 
From cou.: 59 It is interesting to note that these calculations have shown structures with oxide ions in the centre to be lower in energy than those with Mg ions in the centre. De la Puente et al. have attributed this to the enhanced electrostatic interaction stabilising highly charged anions in more highly coordinated sites,15 although later arguments, based on anion polarizability, appear to contradict this.19,20
From Soup: 59 Recio et al. have extracted effective (Mulliken) ionic charges from their HF calculations, 13 showing that the charges range from ±0.81 in the MgO molecule to +1.45(Mg) and −1.34(O) for the 5-coordinate ions in (MgO) 12 . Average ionic charges in (MgO) 12 are ±1.19, with the corresponding calculated charges of the 6-coordinated ions in bulk MgO (with the NaCl structure) being ±1.85.
 ###### 
From cou.: 60 Recio et al. have extracted effective (Mulliken) ionic charges from their HF calculations,13 showing that the charges range from ±0.81 in the MgO molecule to +1.45(Mg) and −1.34(O) for the 5-coordinate ions in (MgO)12. Average ionic charges in (MgO)12 are ±1.19, with the corresponding calculated charges of the 6-coordinated ions in bulk MgO (with the NaCl structure) being ±1.85.
From Soup: 60 De la Puente and colleagues have shown that the effect of introducing electron correlation is to stabilize the hexagonal structures relative to cuboidal structures, 15 so that the transition to bulk-like rock salt structures is shifted to higher nuclearities, a situation which is reversed relative to alkali halide clusters. These hexagonal structures correspond to those found for the rigid ion model, with relatively high ( i.e. close to ±2) formal charges. Ion polarization, on the other hand, tends to favour more compact, cuboidal structures, corresponding to rigid ion model calculations for low ( i.e. close to ±1) charges. The existence of approximately equi-energetic hexagonal and cuboidal families of clusters, explains the experimental mass spectra of MgO clusters 4–7 well.
 ###### 
From cou.: 61 De la Puente and colleagues have shown that the effect of introducing electron correlation is to stabilize the hexagonal structures relative to cuboidal structures,15 so that the transition to bulk-like rock salt structures is shifted to higher nuclearities, a situation which is reversed relative to alkali halide clusters. These hexagonal structures correspond to those found for the rigid ion model, with relatively high (i.e. close to ±2) formal charges. Ion polarization, on the other hand, tends to favour more compact, cuboidal structures, corresponding to rigid ion model calculations for low (i.e. close to ±1) charges. The existence of approximately equi-energetic hexagonal and cuboidal families of clusters, explains the experimental mass spectra of MgO clusters4–7 well.
From Soup: 61 As mentioned in the Introduction, in addition to stoichiometric MgO cluster, the experiments of Saunders 4,5 and of Ziemann and Castleman 6–8 also resulted in the generation of non-stoichiometric (MgO) N Mg + and (MgO) N Mg 2+ clusters. The GA was therefore used to search for the global minima of non-stoichiometric (Mg q + O q − ) N Mg q + clusters with N in the range 5–29, for q = 1 and q = 2.
 ###### 
From cou.: 62 As mentioned in the Introduction, in addition to stoichiometric MgO cluster, the experiments of Saunders4,5 and of Ziemann and Castleman6–8 also resulted in the generation of non-stoichiometric (MgO)NMg+ and (MgO)NMg2+ clusters. The GA was therefore used to search for the global minima of non-stoichiometric (Mgq+Oq−)NMgq+ clusters with N in the range 5–29, for q=1 and q=2.
From Soup: 62 The trends in the geometries of the clusters are similar to those seen in the geometries of the stoichiometric clusters: clusters with ions of charges ±1 tend to be cuboidal structures and those with ions of charges ±2 are cage-like. This is to be expected as the same factors influence the geometries of the stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric clusters modelled with the rigid ion potential. The same cluster geometries are found for N = 12 and N = 13 (MgO) N Mg q + clusters, for both singly and doubly charged ions. The N = 12 cluster has a Mg 4 O 5 3 × 3 square array of ions with two Mg 4 O 4 rings stacked above it. The N = 13 cluster is a 3 × 3 × 3 cube. The ab initio (perturbed ion plus polarization) calculations of Aguado et al . on non-stoichiometric (MgO) N Mg 2+ clusters, 19 indicate that the additional Mg 2+ cation stabilises cuboidal geometries relative to hexagonal stacks. Such cuboidal structures are consistent with some of the intense mass spectral peaks measured by Ziemann and Castleman. 7,8 The preference for cuboidal structures, even at low nuclearities may be because these clusters have an odd number (2 N + 1) of ions, allowing complete cuboidal clusters ( i , j , k ) to be constructed when the product i × j × k is odd, whereas hexagonal prismatic clusters must possess an even number of ions. It has also been shown that the excess charge in these non-stoichiometric (or “defect”) clusters is screened more effectively in cubic clusters. 19
 ###### 
From cou.: 63 The trends in the geometries of the clusters are similar to those seen in the geometries of the stoichiometric clusters: clusters with ions of charges ±1 tend to be cuboidal structures and those with ions of charges ±2 are cage-like. This is to be expected as the same factors influence the geometries of the stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric clusters modelled with the rigid ion potential. The same cluster geometries are found for N=12 and N=13 (MgO)NMgq+ clusters, for both singly and doubly charged ions. The N=12 cluster has a Mg4O5 3×3 square array of ions with two Mg4O4 rings stacked above it. The N=13 cluster is a 3×3×3 cube. The ab initio (perturbed ion plus polarization) calculations of Aguado et al. on non-stoichiometric (MgO)NMg2+ clusters,19 indicate that the additional Mg2+ cation stabilises cuboidal geometries relative to hexagonal stacks. Such cuboidal structures are consistent with some of the intense mass spectral peaks measured by Ziemann and Castleman.7,8 The preference for cuboidal structures, even at low nuclearities may be because these clusters have an odd number (2N+1) of ions, allowing complete cuboidal clusters (i, j, k) to be constructed when the product i×j×k is odd, whereas hexagonal prismatic clusters must possess an even number of ions. It has also been shown that the excess charge in these non-stoichiometric (or “defect”) clusters is screened more effectively in cubic clusters.19
From Soup: 63 The second differences in the binding energies, calculated using the rigid ion model for (Mg + O − ) N Mg + clusters, are shown in Fig. 16 . The most stable clusters, corresponding to large second difference peaks, are those with 27 and 45 ions ( i.e. N = 13 and 22). The rigid ion model calculations of Ziemann and Castleman (with q = 1) also predict these clusters to be particularly stable with respect to loss of MgO molecules. 7 Both of these clusters have cuboidal lattice structures: the 27-ion cluster being an O-centred 3 × 3 × 3 cube and the 45-ion cluster being a 5 × 3 × 3 cuboid, as shown in Fig. 17 . These clusters were found to be magic number clusters by Ziemann and Castlemann. 7
 ###### 
From cou.: 64 The second differences in the binding energies, calculated using the rigid ion model for (Mg+O−)NMg+ clusters, are shown in Fig. 16. The most stable clusters, corresponding to large second difference peaks, are those with 27 and 45 ions (i.e.N=13 and 22). The rigid ion model calculations of Ziemann and Castleman (with q=1) also predict these clusters to be particularly stable with respect to loss of MgO molecules.7 Both of these clusters have cuboidal lattice structures: the 27-ion cluster being an O-centred 3×3×3 cube and the 45-ion cluster being a 5×3×3 cuboid, as shown in Fig. 17. These clusters were found to be magic number clusters by Ziemann and Castlemann.7
From Soup: 64 It is interesting to note that the ab initio perturbed ion plus polarization calculations of Aguado et al. do not find complete cubes or cuboids to be most stable for (MgO) N Mg 2+ clusters with N = 13 and 22. 19 Instead they find flatter defective cuboids in this size range. They have attributed this finding to the fact that the 3 × 3 × 3 and 5 × 3 × 3 complete cuboids possess one and two central (bulk-like) oxide anions, respectively, which are octahedrally coordinated by six Mg cations . Although there is a greater electrostatic (Madelung) stabilization of the oxide anion in this environment, such a configuration is higher in energy than structures in which the oxide ions are all on the surface of the cluster. Oxide ions in low-coordination (and low-symmetry) surface sites have greater polarizabilities, leading to a greater stabilising polarization contribution to the cluster binding energy. Both the 3 × 3 × 3 cube and the 5 × 3 × 3 cuboid have Mg cations at the low-coordinate corner sites. Aguado et al. argue that greater polarization stabilization is gained if these sites are occupied by the much more polarizable oxide anions. This conclusion is supported by the fact that Aguado's calculations predict the Mg-deficient clusters (MgO) 13 O 2− and (MgO) 22 O 2− to have 3 × 3 × 3 and 5 × 3 × 3 structures, respectively, with oxide ions at the corners and fewer 6-coordinate oxides . 19,20 Considering larger (MgO) N Mg 2+ clusters, Aguado et al. predict that bulk-like (more 3-dimensional) cuboids, with a greater number of internal oxide ions, begin to dominate after N = 24. 19
 ###### 
From cou.: 65 It is interesting to note that the ab initio perturbed ion plus polarization calculations of Aguado et al. do not find complete cubes or cuboids to be most stable for (MgO)NMg2+ clusters with N=13 and 22.19 Instead they find flatter defective cuboids in this size range. They have attributed this finding to the fact that the 3×3×3 and 5×3×3 complete cuboids possess one and two central (bulk-like) oxide anions, respectively, which are octahedrally coordinated by six Mg cations. Although there is a greater electrostatic (Madelung) stabilization of the oxide anion in this environment, such a configuration is higher in energy than structures in which the oxide ions are all on the surface of the cluster. Oxide ions in low-coordination (and low-symmetry) surface sites have greater polarizabilities, leading to a greater stabilising polarization contribution to the cluster binding energy. Both the 3×3×3 cube and the 5×3×3 cuboid have Mg cations at the low-coordinate corner sites. Aguado et al. argue that greater polarization stabilization is gained if these sites are occupied by the much more polarizable oxide anions. This conclusion is supported by the fact that Aguado's calculations predict the Mg-deficient clusters (MgO)13O2− and (MgO)22O2− to have 3×3×3 and 5×3×3 structures, respectively, with oxide ions at the corners and fewer 6-coordinate oxides.19,20 Considering larger (MgO)NMg2+ clusters, Aguado et al. predict that bulk-like (more 3-dimensional) cuboids, with a greater number of internal oxide ions, begin to dominate after N=24.19
From Soup: 65 It should be noted that these results of Aguado et al. 19,20 (although giving good agreement with experimental magic numbers and dissociation energies) are in marked disagreement with the earlier findings of the same group 15 and may reflect an over-estimation of the polarization contribution to cluster cohesion. Further studies of the structures and fragmentation patterns of stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric MgO clusters, at a higher level of theory, may help to determine the true structures of these clusters.
 ###### 
From cou.: 66 It should be noted that these results of Aguado et al.19,20 (although giving good agreement with experimental magic numbers and dissociation energies) are in marked disagreement with the earlier findings of the same group15 and may reflect an over-estimation of the polarization contribution to cluster cohesion. Further studies of the structures and fragmentation patterns of stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric MgO clusters, at a higher level of theory, may help to determine the true structures of these clusters.
From Soup: 66 The cluster GA has been shown to be successful at optimizing the geometries of stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric MgO clusters, giving either cuboidal or cage-like structures depending on the formal charges of the ions. The results are repeatable with the same lowest energy structure being found for a high percentage of the different runs (each starting from a different initial population) performed for each cluster nuclearity.
 ###### 
From cou.: 67 The cluster GA has been shown to be successful at optimizing the geometries of stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric MgO clusters, giving either cuboidal or cage-like structures depending on the formal charges of the ions. The results are repeatable with the same lowest energy structure being found for a high percentage of the different runs (each starting from a different initial population) performed for each cluster nuclearity.
From Soup: 67 We have found that the GA, in combination with the rigid ion potential, is able to predict geometries of small MgO clusters that agree reasonably well with the geometries predicted on the basis of ab initio calculations. The cage-like structures predicted by the GA and the rigid-ion model for MgO clusters with formal charges of ±2, however, do not, in general, agree with experimental evidence or higher level ab initio calculations. If the formal charges are reduced towards ±1 then the structures predicted by the GA are in agreement with experimental evidence and higher level ab initio calculations. These alternative structures are either cuboidal structures, based on the bulk NaCl structure, or hexagonal stacks. Complete i × j × k cuboidal structures and hexagonal stacks are consistent with magic numbers found in the mass spectra of MgO clusters. 4–7 As there is always some ambiguity in the interpretation of mass spectral data, alternative information, such as is afforded by ion mobility measurements, 42 may enable the determination of the actual structures of (MgO) N and (MgO) N Mg q + clusters, as a function of size. In this way, some of the disagreements between ab initio , as well as empirical, calculations may be cleared up.
 ###### 
From cou.: 68 We have found that the GA, in combination with the rigid ion potential, is able to predict geometries of small MgO clusters that agree reasonably well with the geometries predicted on the basis of ab initio calculations. The cage-like structures predicted by the GA and the rigid-ion model for MgO clusters with formal charges of ±2, however, do not, in general, agree with experimental evidence or higher level ab initio calculations. If the formal charges are reduced towards ±1 then the structures predicted by the GA are in agreement with experimental evidence and higher level ab initio calculations. These alternative structures are either cuboidal structures, based on the bulk NaCl structure, or hexagonal stacks. Complete i×j×k cuboidal structures and hexagonal stacks are consistent with magic numbers found in the mass spectra of MgO clusters.4–7 As there is always some ambiguity in the interpretation of mass spectral data, alternative information, such as is afforded by ion mobility measurements,42 may enable the determination of the actual structures of (MgO)N and (MgO)NMgq+ clusters, as a function of size. In this way, some of the disagreements between ab initio, as well as empirical, calculations may be cleared up.
From Soup: 68 The deficiency in the rigid ion model that leads to the prediction of the incorrect structures of clusters formed from doubly charged Mg and O ions is the lack of inclusion of the polarizability of the ions (especially that of the oxide anion). The effect of polarizability can be partially mimicked by reducing the formal charges of the cluster ions, and this was shown, in some cases, to give rise to clusters with the correct structures. As Wilson has pointed out, however, the use of partial charges is not desireable if one wishes to produce models which are transferable over a wide range of nuclearities and conformations. 17 In his study of MgO clusters, Wilson adopted a compressible ion model, 47 with coordination number-dependent ionic polarizabilities, which were parametrized to HF calculations. 17 This model is evidently superior to the polarizable ion shell model adopted by Ziemann and Castleman, 7 which was found to lead to little improvement in the agreement between calculated and experimental cluster abundances for high (±2) formal charges.
 ###### 
From cou.: 69 The deficiency in the rigid ion model that leads to the prediction of the incorrect structures of clusters formed from doubly charged Mg and O ions is the lack of inclusion of the polarizability of the ions (especially that of the oxide anion). The effect of polarizability can be partially mimicked by reducing the formal charges of the cluster ions, and this was shown, in some cases, to give rise to clusters with the correct structures. As Wilson has pointed out, however, the use of partial charges is not desireable if one wishes to produce models which are transferable over a wide range of nuclearities and conformations.17 In his study of MgO clusters, Wilson adopted a compressible ion model,47 with coordination number-dependent ionic polarizabilities, which were parametrized to HF calculations.17 This model is evidently superior to the polarizable ion shell model adopted by Ziemann and Castleman,7 which was found to lead to little improvement in the agreement between calculated and experimental cluster abundances for high (±2) formal charges.
From Soup: 69 Wilson's search of configuration space was not exhaustive, being limited to pre-determined “plausible” structures (cuboids, hexagonal stacks etc. ). 17 In future, it would be desirable to combine this model with a robust search algorithm, such as the GA, described here, to explore the potential energy surface of MgO clusters more fully. The global minima from these polarizable ion model calculations could then be investigated by correlated ab initio molecular orbital calculations. An alternative approach, developed by Hartke, 48–50 would be to couple empirical and ab initio calculations, within a GA framework, with a limited number of ab initio data points being used to reparametrize the empirical potential “on-the-fly”.
 ###### 
From cou.: 70 Wilson's search of configuration space was not exhaustive, being limited to pre-determined “plausible” structures (cuboids, hexagonal stacks etc.).17 In future, it would be desirable to combine this model with a robust search algorithm, such as the GA, described here, to explore the potential energy surface of MgO clusters more fully. The global minima from these polarizable ion model calculations could then be investigated by correlated ab initio molecular orbital calculations. An alternative approach, developed by Hartke,48–50 would be to couple empirical and ab initio calculations, within a GA framework, with a limited number of ab initio data points being used to reparametrize the empirical potential “on-the-fly”.
From Soup: 70 Investigation of clusters with intermediate, non-integer charges was found, in many cases, to lead to alternative, low-energy structures, some of which were also found to be low in energy by ab initio calculations. However, there appears to be no well-defined point (value of q ) at which a change in geometry occurs and some geometries remain unchanged across the entire charge range (at least from q = 1–2). As the Coulomb plus Born–Mayer potential of Lewis and Catlow 35 constrains MgO to adopt the NaCl structure in the bulk limit, it would be interesting to study the size at which bulk-like structures take over from hexagonal or cage-like structures, for formal charges of ±2 and to compare these results with the polarizable ion model and ab initio calculations.
 ###### 
From cou.: 71 Investigation of clusters with intermediate, non-integer charges was found, in many cases, to lead to alternative, low-energy structures, some of which were also found to be low in energy by ab initio calculations. However, there appears to be no well-defined point (value of q) at which a change in geometry occurs and some geometries remain unchanged across the entire charge range (at least from q=1–2). As the Coulomb plus Born–Mayer potential of Lewis and Catlow35 constrains MgO to adopt the NaCl structure in the bulk limit, it would be interesting to study the size at which bulk-like structures take over from hexagonal or cage-like structures, for formal charges of ±2 and to compare these results with the polarizable ion model and ab initio calculations.
